    learning:'New DYSPEPSIA temporally linked to a medication change is often IATROGENIC (drug-induced), the commonest culprit being an NSAID, with others including aspirin/antiplatelets, oral bisphosphonates, corticosteroids, SSRIs, iron, calcium-channel blockers, nitrates and theophylline \u2014 so take a history linking onset to the drug. Critically, screen ALARM features that mandate urgent assessment per NICE NG12 (upper-GI): dysphagia, significant unintentional weight loss, GI bleeding (haematemesis/melaena)/iron-deficiency anaemia, persistent vomiting, an epigastric mass, and age \u226555 with persistent, unexplained dyspepsia \u2014 which warrants urgent direct-access endoscopy (2-week-wait) to exclude oesophageal/stomach cancer. The right action is to REVIEW the medication rather than reflexively add acid suppression: where possible stop/switch the culprit (e.g. stop the oral NSAID and use paracetamol or a topical NSAID; lowest effective dose for the shortest time; reconsider the indication), because masking drug-induced symptoms with a PPI while continuing an ulcerogenic NSAID is poor practice. If an NSAID/antiplatelet must continue, co-prescribe a PPI for GASTROPROTECTION, especially with risk factors (age, previous ulcer/bleed, anticoagulants/steroids/SSRIs, H. pylori), and consider H. pylori test-and-treat, with lifestyle advice (weight, alcohol, trigger foods, smoking). Manage per NICE, review the response, escalate/endoscope if dyspepsia persists despite stopping the drug or if red flags emerge, and avoid long-term unreviewed PPIs. The skill is recognising the drug cause, reviewing/rationalising medication rather than just adding a PPI, red-flag/NG12 screening, and gastroprotection. NICE NG12 upper-GI applies where red-flag/age criteria are present.',
