    learning:'A LOW-TRAUMA (fragility) fracture \u2014 from standing height or less \u2014 is itself diagnostic of OSTEOPOROSIS and a strong marker of high future fracture risk, and a vertebral fragility fracture is significant. Long-term/high-dose oral GLUCOCORTICOIDS markedly increase fracture risk rapidly (often before DEXA changes), causing GLUCOCORTICOID-INDUCED OSTEOPOROSIS \u2014 so bone protection should ideally have been considered when long-term steroids were started, and steroids are very likely a major contributor here, which should be acknowledged honestly. Assess fracture risk (FRAX \u00b1 DEXA), but in a patient on long-term steroids with a fragility fracture START bone protection now \u2014 a BISPHOSPHONATE (e.g. alendronate) with calcium/vitamin D \u2014 often without waiting for DEXA, because a fragility fracture/high-dose steroid is itself a treatment indication; counsel bisphosphonate administration (upright, with water, before food, oesophageal cautions) and monitoring. Review the glucocorticoid (lowest effective dose, taper where possible, steroid-sparing agents/specialist review) to reduce ongoing bone and other harm. Address falls risk (assessment/prevention), lifestyle (weight-bearing exercise, smoking, alcohol, adequate calcium/vitamin D) and fracture care (analgesia, mobilisation, physiotherapy), and briefly consider other causes of vertebral fracture with red flags (e.g. myeloma/metastasis \u2014 unexplained, systemic features) \u2014 investigating if atypical. Communicate honestly and openly (a candour-style, non-defensive acknowledgement that steroids contributed and bone protection is now needed) without blame, apologising appropriately if protection was missed, and focus on putting it right with future bone monitoring. No NICE NG12 cancer pathway applies unless red flags suggest myeloma/metastasis.',
